<div class="tab-content active" id="notes-2-6">
  <div class="callout remember">
    <div class="callout-title">Note</div>
    <p>This section is pending teacher review.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Price Elasticity of Supply (PES)</h2>

    <div class="formula-box">
      <div class="formula-label">Price Elasticity of Supply</div>
      <div class="formula">PES = % change in quantity supplied ÷ % change in price</div>
    </div>

    <p>PES is always <strong>positive</strong> — as price rises, quantity supplied rises (positive relationship).</p>

    <h3>Degrees of PES</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Value</th><th>Description</th><th>Diagram shape</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>PES > 1</td><td>Relatively elastic</td><td>Shallow upward slope; intercepts the price axis</td></tr>
        <tr><td>PES &lt; 1</td><td>Relatively inelastic</td><td>Steep upward slope; intercepts the quantity axis</td></tr>
        <tr><td>PES = 1</td><td>Unitary elastic</td><td>Straight line through the origin</td></tr>
        <tr><td>PES = 0</td><td>Perfectly inelastic</td><td>Vertical supply curve</td></tr>
        <tr><td>PES = ∞</td><td>Perfectly elastic</td><td>Horizontal supply curve</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="callout exam-tip">
      <div class="callout-title">Diagram tip</div>
      <p>A useful rule: any straight-line supply curve that passes through the <strong>price axis</strong> (above origin) is elastic. Any that passes through the <strong>quantity axis</strong> is inelastic. Any through the <strong>origin</strong> has PES = 1.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Determinants of PES</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Determinant</th><th>Effect</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Time period</strong></td><td>Supply is more elastic in the long run — firms have time to invest in new capacity, hire labour, or switch production</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Mobility of factors of production</strong></td><td>If factors can be easily moved between uses (e.g., general machinery), supply is more elastic</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Unused capacity</strong></td><td>Firms with spare capacity can increase output quickly without new investment — more elastic supply</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Ability to store output</strong></td><td>Storable goods (e.g., manufactured products) are more elastic — firms can release stocks in response to price changes. Perishable goods (e.g., fresh fish) are less elastic.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Rate at which costs increase</strong></td><td>If increasing output causes rapid cost increases, firms are less willing to expand — supply is less elastic</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="callout hl-only">
      <div class="callout-title">HL only — Primary commodities vs manufactured goods</div>
      <p>Primary commodities (e.g., wheat, copper, cocoa) tend to have <strong>lower PES</strong> than manufactured products because:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Production depends on natural factors (land, climate) that cannot be rapidly scaled up</li>
        <li>Growing seasons and biological limits prevent quick supply responses</li>
        <li>Factors of production in agriculture are relatively immobile</li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin-top:0.5rem;">Manufactured goods generally have higher PES because firms can expand factory output, hire workers, or increase machine hours relatively quickly.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <div class="recap-title">Key points to remember</div>
    <ul>
      <li>PES = %ΔQs ÷ %ΔP; always positive</li>
      <li>PES > 1 = elastic; PES &lt; 1 = inelastic</li>
      <li>Determinants: time, factor mobility, unused capacity, storability, cost behaviour</li>
      <li>Supply is more elastic in the long run than the short run</li>
      <li>Primary commodities have lower PES than manufactured goods (HL)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="tab-content" id="worked-2-6">
  <div class="callout remember">
    <div class="callout-title">Note</div>
    <p>Worked examples are pending teacher review.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Worked Example — PES Calculation</h2>
  <p>The price of wheat rises from $200 to $240 per tonne. Farmers increase supply from 5,000 to 5,400 tonnes.</p>

  <h3>Step 1: Calculate % change in Qs</h3>
  <div class="answer-content" style="display:block;">
    % ΔQs = (5,400 − 5,000) ÷ 5,000 × 100 = +8%
  </div>

  <h3>Step 2: Calculate % change in price</h3>
  <div class="answer-content" style="display:block;">
    % ΔP = (240 − 200) ÷ 200 × 100 = +20%
  </div>

  <h3>Step 3: Calculate PES</h3>
  <div class="answer-content" style="display:block;">
    PES = 8% ÷ 20% = <strong>0.4</strong><br>
    PES &lt; 1 → supply is <strong>price inelastic</strong> — a 20% price rise causes only an 8% increase in quantity supplied.
  </div>

  <h3>Interpretation</h3>
  <div class="answer-content" style="display:block;">
    This is consistent with wheat being a primary commodity. Farmers cannot rapidly expand output in response to price signals — they are constrained by land availability, growing seasons, and time needed to plant and harvest.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="tab-content" id="practice-2-6">
  <div class="callout remember">
    <div class="callout-title">Note</div>
    <p>Practice questions are pending teacher review.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="exercises">
    <div class="exercises-title">Practice Questions</div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">1. Price rises from $50 to $60. Quantity supplied increases from 800 to 920. Calculate PES and state whether supply is elastic or inelastic.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          %ΔQs = (920 − 800) ÷ 800 × 100 = +15%<br>
          %ΔP = (60 − 50) ÷ 50 × 100 = +20%<br>
          PES = 15% ÷ 20% = <strong>0.75</strong><br>
          PES &lt; 1 → supply is <strong>price inelastic</strong>.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">2. Explain why supply of oil is more inelastic in the short run than in the long run.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          In the short run, oil companies cannot quickly expand output because they are limited by existing wells, drilling capacity, and infrastructure. Exploring new fields and building pipelines takes years. In the long run, however, oil companies can invest in new exploration, drill additional wells, and expand refining capacity — making supply more responsive to price increases. This illustrates the general principle that PES is greater (more elastic) in the long run than the short run.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">3. Compare the likely PES of (a) fresh strawberries and (b) frozen strawberries. Explain the difference.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          Fresh strawberries have lower PES than frozen strawberries. Fresh strawberries are perishable — supply cannot be easily adjusted by releasing stored inventory, and production is tied to the growing season. Frozen strawberries, by contrast, can be stockpiled — producers can release more from frozen storage when price rises, making supply more responsive. This illustrates how the ability to store output increases PES.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

